  <!-- ── Component 5: State Machine ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="comp-statemachine" class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 pb-12">
    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
      <span class="text-3xl">⚙️</span>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white">State Machine</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm mb-5 leading-relaxed">
      Raft doesn't care what your state machine does — it just guarantees every live node applies the
      same commands in the same order. The state machine is your application logic on top of the consensus layer.
      The interface is minimal: <code class="text-purple-300">Apply(command) → result</code>.
    </p>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-3 mb-6">
      {[
        { name: 'Key-Value store', used: 'etcd, Consul KV', desc: 'The classic. Commands are SET/GET/DEL. Every node applies them to a local map. Simple to verify correctness.', code: 'type KV map[string]string\nfunc Apply(cmd) {\n  if cmd.op == SET\n    kv[cmd.key] = cmd.val\n}' },
        { name: 'SQL engine', used: 'CockroachDB, TiDB', desc: 'Commands are SQL statements or KV operations. State machine is a B-tree or LSM. Each Raft group manages a shard.', code: 'func Apply(cmd) {\n  txn := db.Begin()\n  txn.Execute(cmd.sql)\n  txn.Commit()\n}' },
        { name: 'Custom FSM', used: 'Kafka KRaft, Vault', desc: 'Anything deterministic. Kafka stores topic/partition metadata. Vault stores secret leases and policies.', code: 'func Apply(cmd) {\n  switch cmd.type {\n  case CREATE_TOPIC:\n    topics[cmd.name] = cmd\n  }\n}' },
      ].map(a => (
        <div class="bg-slate-900 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-4">
          <div class="font-semibold text-white text-sm mb-1">{a.name}</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-sky-400 mb-2 font-mono">{a.used}</div>
          <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 mb-3 leading-relaxed">{a.desc}</p>
          <pre class="text-xs text-slate-400 bg-slate-950 rounded p-2 overflow-x-auto leading-relaxed">{a.code}</pre>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
    <div class="bg-slate-900 border border-purple-800/40 rounded-xl p-5">
      <h3 class="text-white font-semibold mb-2 text-sm">The golden rule: determinism</h3>
      <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
        Your state machine <strong class="text-white">must be deterministic</strong> — given the same sequence of commands,
        every node must produce exactly the same state. This means: no random(), no time.now(), no external reads
        inside Apply(). If you need timestamps, include them in the command itself so all nodes use the same value.
        Non-determinism is how you get split-brain even with correct Raft.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Component 6: Snapshots ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="comp-snapshot" class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 pb-12">
    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
      <span class="text-3xl">📸</span>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white">Snapshots &amp; Log Compaction</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm mb-5 leading-relaxed">
      Without compaction, the log grows forever. A snapshot captures the full state machine at a given log index,
      then the log up to that point is discarded. New nodes joining the cluster receive the snapshot instead of
      replaying the entire log — which could be millions of entries.
    </p>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
      <div class="bg-slate-900 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
        <h3 class="text-white font-semibold mb-3 text-sm">InstallSnapshot RPC</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 leading-relaxed mb-3">
          When a follower is too far behind (nextIndex is before the leader's log start),
          the leader sends a snapshot instead of log entries. The follower replaces its entire state.
        </p>
        <div class="font-mono text-xs space-y-1">
          <div class="text-rose-400">InstallSnapshot(args) → reply</div>
          <div class="text-slate-500">  term              uint64</div>
          <div class="text-slate-500">  leaderId          NodeId</div>
          <div class="text-slate-500">  lastIncludedIndex uint64</div>
          <div class="text-slate-500">  lastIncludedTerm  uint64</div>
          <div class="text-slate-500">  data              []byte  // state machine state</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-slate-900 border border-slate-700 rounded-xl p-5">
        <h3 class="text-white font-semibold mb-3 text-sm">When to take a snapshot</h3>
        <div class="space-y-2 text-xs text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
          <div><span class="text-slate-200 font-semibold">Log size threshold</span> — snapshot when log exceeds N MB. Simple, common in practice.</div>
          <div><span class="text-slate-200 font-semibold">Time-based</span> — snapshot every T minutes. Predictable storage growth, but may snapshot too often or too rarely.</div>
          <div><span class="text-slate-200 font-semibold">On membership change</span> — snapshot before a new node joins. Ensures fast bootstrap.</div>
          <div class="text-amber-400">⚠ Never snapshot while holding a lock on the state machine — use copy-on-write or a background thread.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Separator ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 pb-8">
    <div class="border-t border-slate-700 pt-10">
